TY  - JOUR
T1  - Wicked Crises and the (In)capacity to Act
AU  - Meyer, Renate E.
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1177/00018392251363998
DO  - 10.1177/00018392251363998
T2  - Administrative Science Quarterly
JF  - Administrative Science Quarterly
SP  - 867
EP  - 883
VL  - 70
IS  - 4
PB  - SAGE Publications Inc
N2  - A crisis is a juncture that demands decision and action. We live in times of wicked crises, that is, crises that are non-linearly interlinked; transgress organizational, institutional, and cultural boundaries; and can be addressed only collectively. Our chances to rise to wicked crises depend on our capacity to decide and to act in concert, which is power, according to political philosopher Hannah Arendt. In this essay, in honor of Administrative Science Quarterly?s 70th volume, I highlight different features of wicked crises and discuss two interrelated forces that weaken and undermine such power: first, organizational fragmentation, which results in governance complexity and fault lines, and second, societal fragmentation, which manifests in growing distrust in core cultural institutions, polarization, the loss of a shared lifeworld, and the rise of authoritarianism. I conclude with a call to action for our discipline.
SN  - 0001-8392
M3  - doi: 10.1177/00018392251363998
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1177/00018392251363998
Y2  - 2026/04/24
